Situated between the Red Sea and the Dead Sea and inhabited since prehistoric times, Petra, the rock-cut capital city of Jordan, was "lost" to the Western world for hundreds of years. Into the cliff faces, the people of Petra carved hundreds of exquisite temples, tombs and monuments. Many have spectacular facades with carved columns, often in styles copied from the buildings of Greece and Rome. Most impressive of all is the front of the Treasury, which is 28 metres wide and 40 metres high. Located amid rugged desert canyons and mountains, Petra was once a thriving trading center and the capital of the Nabataean empire between 400 B.C. and A.D. 106. The city sat empty and in near ruin for centuries. Only in the early 1800s did a European traveler disguise himself in Arab costume and sneak into the mysterious area. In 1985, the Petra Archaeological Park was declared a UNESCO World Heritage site, and about 2 decades after that, it was named one of the new seven wonders of the world.

Between about 200 BC and AD 400, it was the busy capital of the Arab kingdom of the Nabataeans. Hidden away among red sandstone hills and surrounded by cliffs, it was the perfect desert hideaway. Into the cliff faces, the people of Petra carved hundreds of exquisite temples, tombs and monuments. Many have spectacular facades (fronts) with carved columns and lintels, often in styles copied from the buildings of Greece and Rome. Most impressive of all is the front of the Treasury, which is 28 metres wide and 40 metres high.
